<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-17T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-17T11:00:00-05:00" n="660" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d660">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">663.119/orig: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-17T16:00:00+00:00">December 17, 1918—4 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received 5:16 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>6340. War Trade Board [from Taylor]: No. 692, attention White. We have made
                        no agreement that consignments to Adriatic ports should depend on War Trade
                        Board receiving import authorization from Inter-Allied Bureau and no such
                        organization exists at present. War Trade Board must not sign away liberty
                        of action. Taylor.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>